\newlabel{thm:stab}{{2}{4}{}{section.4}{}}
\newlabel{thm:nonid}{{3}{5}{}{section.4}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces Representative stabilization patterns across one-, two-, and three-dimensional rules. The top row shows selected period versus horizon; the bottom row shows the NML margin to the runner-up candidate. After the final transition, margins grow rather than shrink. This is the empirical signature expected when the asymptotic rate gap dominates the logarithmic complexity penalty.}}{6}{figure.2}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:stabilization}{{2}{6}{Representative stabilization patterns across one-, two-, and three-dimensional rules. The top row shows selected period versus horizon; the bottom row shows the NML margin to the runner-up candidate. After the final transition, margins grow rather than shrink. This is the empirical signature expected when the asymptotic rate gap dominates the logarithmic complexity penalty}{figure.2}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3}{\ignorespaces Selector comparison on 105 nontrivial Life-like rules at $T=100$. Raw residual minimization and Bernoulli NLL are pulled toward larger periods because fit can only improve along divisibility chains. The Bernoulli NML penalty prevents that period inflation and yields parsimonious selections.}}{7}{figure.3}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:ablation}{{3}{7}{Selector comparison on 105 nontrivial Life-like rules at $T=100$. Raw residual minimization and Bernoulli NLL are pulled toward larger periods because fit can only improve along divisibility chains. The Bernoulli NML penalty prevents that period inflation and yields parsimonious selections}{figure.3}{}}
\bibcite{boccara1999}{{1}{}{{}}{{}}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4}{\ignorespaces Entropy-rate decomposition for rules 54, 110, and 30. The raw spacetime is deterministic given a sufficient local context. The periodic background retains nearly all of that predictability, while the residual mask has much lower conditional entropy than marginal entropy. This indicates that the residual is not just random noise; it retains internal spatiotemporal structure consistent with particle-like dynamics.}}{8}{figure.4}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:entropy}{{4}{8}{Entropy-rate decomposition for rules 54, 110, and 30. The raw spacetime is deterministic given a sufficient local context. The periodic background retains nearly all of that predictability, while the residual mask has much lower conditional entropy than marginal entropy. This indicates that the residual is not just random noise; it retains internal spatiotemporal structure consistent with particle-like dynamics}{figure.4}{}}
